                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="15197" author="balex" created="Wed, 2 Nov 2005 19:25:29 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The InteractiveAuthenticationSuccessEvent now subclasses AbstractAuthenticationEvent, which was part of a refactor of event handling as per &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-70&quot; title=&quot;Refactor event publishing to make less dependent on DaoAuthenticationProvider&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SEC-70&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SEC-70&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A new task, &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-72&quot; title=&quot;Refactor authentication mechanisms for more consistent approach&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SEC-72&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SEC-72&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, has been create to add more consistency to the authentication mechanisms, which was the second half of the &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SEC-71&quot; title=&quot;InteractiveAuthenticationSuccessEvent  should extend AuthenticationEvent&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SEC-71&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SEC-71&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; request.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15566" author="balex" created="Fri, 25 Nov 2005 15:36:11 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;What is being initialized? Could you do it from within your AuthenticationProvider? So you have an InitializingAuthenticationProvider registered in the ProviderManager which simply proxies your real AuthenticationProvider, such as DaoAuthenticationProvider. Alternatively, could you use the authentication event mechanisms to achieve the same initialization?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We could add an interface that allows a shared callback, so you need to register it in the IoC container as opposed to subclassing either AbstractProcessingFilter or TokenBasedRememberMeServices. However, it would help in designing the interface&apos;s method signature to know what you&apos;re trying to do.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="15569" author="pathos" created="Fri, 25 Nov 2005 18:31:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Use case is &apos;upon successful login, increment the login count and last login date&apos;. I guess now this could be done using the event system.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="126713" author="issuemaster" created="Sat, 6 Feb 2016 06:35:36 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This issue has been migrated to &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/332&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-security/issues/332&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
